# Frontend Spec

## Scope

React UI architecture, shared state, route-level pages, CSS system, and store/cart
frontend contracts.

## Load when

Changing React components, page routes, atoms/hooks, CSS, cart/store UI,
WebSocket consumers, or page-builder UX.

## Owns

- App shell/routes: `frontend/src/App.tsx`, `frontend/src/pages/routes.tsx`,
  `frontend/src/pages/Layout.tsx`
- State: `frontend/src/atoms/*`
- API utilities: `frontend/src/utils/api.ts`
- WebSocket singleton: `frontend/src/hooks/useWebSocketSync.ts`
- Design tokens/utilities: `frontend/src/index.css`, `frontend/src/utilities.css`
- Domain pages/components: `src/pages/*`, `src/components/*`, `src/styles/*`

## Architecture Contracts

- React + TypeScript + Vite.
- Jotai atoms are the cross-page state boundary.
- REST is used for initial reads and mutations; mutable shared state converges
  through WebSocket pushes into atoms.
- `useWebSocketSync` is mounted by `Layout.tsx` and can be called by consumers
  for `subscribe`/`unsubscribe`; it must remain a singleton per browser context.
- Route pages live under `src/pages`; reusable domain UI lives under
  `src/components`; shared CSS tokens live only in `src/index.css`.
- Page-section types, config aliases, versions, defaults, and capabilities in
  `sectionContracts.generated.ts` are generated from backend canonical schemas;
  update them with `npm run contracts:generate`, never by hand.
- New normalized page-section boundaries use `PageSection<T>` with generated
  shell and per-type config. Existing document renderers use `LegacyPageSection`
  until migrated; `sectionAdapter.ts` is the compatibility owner for object/string
  configs, legacy aliases/keys, runtime separation, quarantine, and reverse
  projection. Backend schema validation remains authoritative.
- Every registered or unsupported page section renders through one
  `SectionFrame`. The frame owns shared presentation, collapse, and the single
  toolbar; renderers may portal type-specific actions into it but must not create
  block-local shared shell controls. Renderers retain semantic heading placement
  and inline content editing where their DOM contracts differ.
- Page palettes expose only declared safe values through namespaced
  `--skaia-page-color-*` variables. Section colors use generated
  inherit/literal/palette sources; content scale applies to an overflow-safe
  inner wrapper, never the toolbar or outer section box.
- `PageBuilderDoc.theme` may carry the generated optional page theme during the
  legacy document compatibility window.
- `PageBuilderDoc.typed_section_mutations` is a backend-owned, per-page cutover
  signal. When true, `PageBuilder` adapts legacy renderer values through
  `typedSectionApi.ts`, batches updates by stable legacy key, sends expected
  server revisions, and uses typed create/delete/reorder operations. A `409`
  discards no server state: the builder explains the conflict and refetches.
- Normalized read cutover is backend-owned and preserves the existing
  `Page.Content` response envelope, so renderers and `usePageData` do not branch
  on storage mode. Reconnect/refetch behavior therefore remains identical when
  `PAGE_NORMALIZED_SECTION_READS` changes authority.
- Datasource-backed reusable designs use the `SectionPreset` type and
  `/config/section-presets`; `CustomSection` remains a deprecated type alias and
  the backend retains the old route during the compatibility window.

